# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rq-queue
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] An **in-memory database** (**IMDb**, or **main memory database system** (**MMDB**) or **memory resident database**) is a database management system that primarily relies on main memory for computer data storage.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] It is contrasted with database management systems that employ a disk storage mechanism.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] In-memory databases are faster than disk-optimized databases because disk access is slower than memory access and the internal optimization algorithms are simpler and execute fewer CPU instructions.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] Accessing data in memory eliminates seek time when querying the data, which provides faster and more predictable performance than disk.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] Applications where response time is critical, such as those running telecommunications network equipment and mobile advertising networks, often use main-memory databases.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] IMDBs have gained much traction, especially in the data analytics space, starting in the mid-2000s – mainly due to multi-core processors that can address large memory and due to less expensive RAM.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] A potential technical hurdle with in-memory data storage is the volatility of RAM.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] Specifically in the event of a power loss, intentional or otherwise, data stored in volatile RAM is lost.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] With the introduction of non-volatile random-access memory technology, in-memory databases will be able to run at full speed and maintain data in the event of power failure.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] In its simplest form, main memory databases store data on volatile memory devices.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] These devices lose all stored information when the device loses power or is reset.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] In this case, IMDBs can be said to lack support for the "durability" portion of the ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) properties.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] Volatile memory-based IMDBs can, and often do, support the other three ACID properties of atomicity, consistency and isolation.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] While storing data in-memory confers performance advantages, it is an expensive method of data storage.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] An approach to realising the benefits of in-memory storage while limiting its costs is to store the most frequently accessed data in-memory and the rest on disk.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] Since there is no hard distinction between which data should be stored in-memory and which should be stored on disk, some systems dynamically update where data is stored based on the data's usage.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] This approach is subtly different from caching, in which the most *recently accessed* data is cached, as opposed to the most *frequently accessed* data being stored in-memory.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] In the cloud computing industry the terms "data temperature", or "hot data" and "cold data" have emerged to describe how data is stored in this respect.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] Hot data is used to describe mission-critical data that needs to be accessed frequently while cold data describes data that is needed less often and less urgently, such as data kept for archiving or auditing purposes.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] Hot data should be stored in ways offering fast retrieval and modification, often accomplished by in-memory storage but not always.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] Cold data on the other hand can be stored in a more cost-effective way and is accepted that data access will likely be slower compared to hot data.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] While these descriptions are useful, "hot" and "cold" lack concrete definitions.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] Manufacturing efficiency provides another reason for selecting a combined in-memory/on-disk database system.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] Some device product lines, especially in consumer electronics, include some units with permanent storage, and others that rely on memory for storage (set-top boxes, for example).
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] If such devices require a database system, a manufacturer can adopt a hybrid database system at lower and *upper* cost, and with less customization of code, rather than using separate in-memory and on-disk databases, respectively, for its disk-less and disk-based products.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] The first database engine to support both in-memory and on-disk tables in a single database, WebDNA, was released in 1995.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] Another variation involves large amounts of nonvolatile memory in the server, for example, flash memory chips as addressable memory rather than structured as disk arrays.
[src:rq-queue/in-memory-database] A database in this form of memory combines very fast access speed with persistence over reboots and power losses.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] In computer science, **message queues** and **mailboxes** are software-engineering components typically used for inter-process communication (IPC), or for inter-thread communication within the same process.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] They use a queue for messaging – the passing of control or of content.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Group communication systems provide similar kinds of functionality.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] The message queue paradigm is a sibling of the publisher/subscriber pattern, and is typically one part of a larger message-oriented middleware system.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Most messaging systems support both the publisher/subscriber and message queue models in their API, e.g.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Competing Consumers pattern enables multiple concurrent consumers to process messages on the same message queue.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Message queues implement an asynchronous communication pattern between two or more processes/threads whereby the sending and receiving party do not need to interact with the message queue at the same time.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Messages placed onto the queue are stored until the recipient retrieves them.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Message queues have implicit or explicit limits on the size of data that may be transmitted in a single message and the number of messages that may remain outstanding on the queue.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Many implementations of message queues function internally within an operating system or within an application.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Such queues exist for the purposes of that system only.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Other implementations allow the passing of messages between different computer systems, potentially connecting multiple applications and multiple operating systems.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] These message queuing systems typically provide resilience functionality to ensure that messages do not get "lost" in the event of a system failure.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Examples of commercial implementations of this kind of message queuing software (also known as message-oriented middleware) include IBM MQ (formerly MQ Series) and Oracle Advanced Queuing (AQ).
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] There is a Java standard called Java Message Service, which has several proprietary and free software implementations.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Real-time operating systems (RTOSes) such as VxWorks and QNX encourage the use of message queuing as the primary inter-process or inter-thread communication mechanism.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] This can result in integration between message passing and CPU scheduling.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Early examples of commercial RTOSes that encouraged a message-queue basis to inter-thread communication also include VRTX and pSOS+, both of which date to the early 1980s.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] The Erlang programming language uses *processes* to provide concurrency; these processes communicate asynchronously using message queuing.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] The message queue software can be either proprietary, open source or a mix of both.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] It is then run either on premise in private servers or on external cloud servers (message queuing service).
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Examples on hardware-based messaging middleware vendors are Solace, Apigee, and IBM MQ.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] In a typical message-queueing implementation, a system administrator installs and configures message-queueing software (a queue manager or broker), and defines a named message queue.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Or they register with a message queuing service.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] An application then registers a software routine that "listens" for messages placed onto the queue.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Second and subsequent applications may connect to the queue and transfer a message onto it.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] The queue-manager software stores the messages until a receiving application connects and then calls the registered software routine.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] The receiving application then processes the message in an appropriate manner.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] These are all considerations that can have substantial effects on transaction semantics, system reliability, and system efficiency.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Historically, message queuing has used proprietary, closed protocols, restricting the ability for different operating systems or programming languages to interact in a heterogeneous set of environments.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] An early attempt to make message queuing more ubiquitous was Sun Microsystems' JMS specification, which provided a Java-only abstraction of a client API.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] This allowed Java developers to switch between providers of message queuing in a fashion similar to that of developers using SQL databases.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] In practice, given the diversity of message queuing techniques and scenarios, this wasn't always as practical as it could be.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] These protocols are at different stages of standardization and adoption.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] The first two operate at the same level as HTTP, MQTT at the level of TCP/IP.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Some proprietary implementations also use HTTP to provide message queuing by some implementations, such as Amazon's SQS.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] This is because it is always possible to layer asynchronous behaviour (which is what is required for message queuing) over a synchronous protocol using request-response semantics.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] However, such implementations are constrained by the underlying protocol in this case and may not be able to offer the full fidelity or set of options required in message passing above.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Many of the more widely known communications protocols in use operate synchronously.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] The HTTP protocol – used in the World Wide Web and in web services – offers an obvious example where a user sends a request for a web page and then waits for a reply.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] However, scenarios exist in which synchronous behaviour is not appropriate.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] For example, AJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML) can be used to asynchronously send text, JSON or XML messages to update part of a web page with more relevant information.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Google uses this approach for their Google Suggest, a search feature which sends the user's partially typed queries to Google's servers and returns a list of possible full queries the user might be interested in the process of typing.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] This list is asynchronously updated as the user types.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Other asynchronous examples exist in event notification systems and publish/subscribe systems.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] In both of the above examples it would not make sense for the sender of the information to have to wait if, for example, one of the recipients had crashed.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Applications need not be exclusively synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] In all these sorts of situations, having a subsystem which performs message-queuing (or alternatively, a broadcast messaging system) can help improve the behavior of the overall system.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] There are two common message queue implementations in UNIX.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] One is part of the SYS V API, the other one is part of POSIX.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] UNIX SYS V implements message passing by keeping an array of linked lists as message queues.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Each message queue is identified by its index in the array, and has a unique descriptor.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] A given index can have multiple possible descriptors.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] UNIX gives standard functions to access the message passing feature.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] This system call takes a key as an argument and returns a descriptor of the queue with the matching key if it exists.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] flag is set, it makes a new message queue with the given key and returns its descriptor.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Used to receive a message from a given queue descriptor.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] The caller process must have read permissions for the queue.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Used to change message queue parameters like the owner.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] A message queue can be deleted only by its creator, owner, or the superuser.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] The POSIX.1-2001 message queue API is the later of the two UNIX message queue APIs.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] It is distinct from the SYS V API, but provides similar function.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] The unix man page `mq_overview(7)` provides an overview of POSIX message queues.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] Graphical user interfaces (GUIs) employ a message queue, also called an *event queue* or *input queue*, to pass graphical input actions, such as mouse clicks, keyboard events, or other user inputs, to the application program.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] The windowing system places messages indicating user or other events, such as timer ticks or messages sent by other threads, into the message queue.
[src:rq-queue/message-queue] The GUI application removes these events one at a time by calling a routine called `getNextEvent()` or similar in an event loop, and then calling the appropriate application routine to process that event.
[src:rq-queue/page] A *job* is a Python object, representing a function that is invoked asynchronously in a worker (background) process.
[src:rq-queue/page] Any Python function can be invoked asynchronously, by simply pushing a reference to the function and its arguments onto a queue.
[src:rq-queue/page] RQ supports Redis >= 5 and Valkey >= 7.2.
[src:rq-queue/page] There’s nothing special about this function!
[src:rq-queue/page] Any Python function call can be put on an RQ queue.
[src:rq-queue/page] Notice the `Queue('low')` in the example above?
[src:rq-queue/page] You can use any queue name, so you can quite flexibly distribute work to your own desire.
[src:rq-queue/page] A common naming pattern is to name your queues after priorities (e.g.
[src:rq-queue/page] In addition, you can add a few options to modify the behaviour of the queued job.
[src:rq-queue/page] By default, these are popped out of the kwargs that will be passed to the job function.
[src:rq-queue/page] For cases where the web process doesn’t have access to the source code running in the worker (i.e. code base X invokes a delayed function from code base Y), you can pass the function as a string reference, too.
[src:rq-queue/page] `Queue.prepare_data` accepts all arguments that `Queue.parse_args` does.
[src:rq-queue/page] If all of a group’s jobs expire or are deleted, the group is removed from Redis.
[src:rq-queue/page] RQ allows you to enforce job uniqueness and deduplicate jobs, preventing the same jobs from being executed multiple times.
[src:rq-queue/page] The uniqueness constraint lasts until the job is deleted.
[src:rq-queue/page] RQ allows you to chain the execution of multiple jobs.
[src:rq-queue/page] The ability to handle job dependencies allows you to split a big job into several smaller ones.
[src:rq-queue/page] By default, a job that is dependent on another is enqueued only when its dependency finishes *successfully*.
[src:rq-queue/page] If you want a job’s dependencies to execute regardless if the job completes or fails, RQ provides the `Dependency` class that will allow you to dictate how to handle job failures.
[src:rq-queue/page] If you want to execute a function whenever a job completes, fails, or is stopped, RQ provides `on_success`, `on_failure`, and `on_stopped` callbacks.
[src:rq-queue/page] RQ lets you configure the method and timeout for each callback - success, failure, and stopped.
[src:rq-queue/page] To configure callback timeouts, use RQ’s `Callback` object that accepts `func` and `timeout` arguments.
[src:rq-queue/page] Success callbacks must be a function that accepts `job`, `connection` and `result` arguments.
[src:rq-queue/page] Your function should also accept `*args` and `**kwargs` so your application doesn’t break when additional parameters are added.
[src:rq-queue/page] Success callbacks are executed after job execution is complete, before dependents are enqueued.
[src:rq-queue/page] If an exception happens when your callback is executed, job status will be set to `FAILED` and dependents won’t be enqueued.
[src:rq-queue/page] Callbacks are limited to 60 seconds of execution time.
[src:rq-queue/page] If you want to execute a long running job, consider using RQ’s job dependency feature instead.
[src:rq-queue/page] Failure callbacks are functions that accept `job`, `connection`, `type`, `value` and `traceback` arguments.
[src:rq-queue/page] `type`, `value` and `traceback` values returned by sys.exc_info(), which is the exception raised when executing your job.
[src:rq-queue/page] Failure callbacks are limited to 60 seconds of execution time.
[src:rq-queue/page] Stopped callbacks are functions that accept `job` and `connection` arguments.
[src:rq-queue/page] Stopped callbacks are functions that are executed when a worker receives a command to stop a job that is currently executing.
[src:rq-queue/page] If you prefer enqueueing jobs via the command line interface or do not use python you can use this.
[src:rq-queue/page] Where `[key]` is the keyword and `[value]` is the value which is parsed with the corresponding parsing method.
[src:rq-queue/page] If the first character of `[value]` is `@` the subsequent path will be read.
[src:rq-queue/page] Webhooks notify an external HTTP endpoint when a job reaches a terminal state (`finished` or `failed`).
[src:rq-queue/page] They are useful for monitoring, status pings and audit trails.
[src:rq-queue/page] To be notified on both outcomes, pass one `Webhook` for each.
[src:rq-queue/page] The `webhooks` argument is also accepted by `enqueue_call`, `enqueue_at` and `enqueue_in`, the `@job` decorator, and `Queue.prepare_data()` for `enqueue_many`.
[src:rq-queue/page] Cron jobs can use webhooks for heartbeat monitoring; see cron jobs.
[src:rq-queue/page] `failed` POST webhooks additionally include `exc_info` (the exception traceback).
[src:rq-queue/page] Delivery is best-effort: send errors (unreachable endpoint, timeout, HTTP error) are logged and swallowed, so a failing webhook never affects job execution.
[src:rq-queue/page] Sending is blocking, so a slow endpoint can delay the worker by up to `timeout` seconds.
[src:rq-queue/page] With RQ, you don’t have to set up any queues upfront, and you don’t have to specify any channels, exchanges, routing rules or whatnot.
[src:rq-queue/page] You can just put jobs onto any queue you want.
[src:rq-queue/page] As soon as you enqueue a job to a queue that does not exist yet, it is created on the fly.
[src:rq-queue/page] RQ does *not* use an advanced broker to do the message routing for you.
[src:rq-queue/page] You may consider this an awesome advantage or a handicap, depending on the problem you’re solving.
[src:rq-queue/page] Lastly, it does not speak a portable protocol, since it depends on pickle to serialize the jobs, so it’s a Python-only system.
[src:rq-queue/page] When jobs get enqueued, the `queue.enqueue()` method returns a `Job` instance.
[src:rq-queue/page] This is nothing more than a proxy object that can be used to check the outcome of the actual job.
[src:rq-queue/page] For this purpose, it has a convenience `result` accessor property, that will return `None` when the job is not yet finished, or a non-`None` value when the job has finished (assuming the job *has* a return value in the first place, of course).
[src:rq-queue/page] If you’re familiar with Celery, you might be used to its `@task` decorator.
[src:rq-queue/page] For testing purposes, you can enqueue jobs without delegating the actual execution to a worker (available since version 0.3.1).
[src:rq-queue/page] The above code runs without an active worker and executes `fib(8)` synchronously within the same process.
[src:rq-queue/page] You may know this behaviour from Celery as `ALWAYS_EAGER`.
[src:rq-queue/page] Note, however, that you still need a working connection to a redis instance for storing states related to job execution and completion.
[src:rq-queue/page] To learn about workers, see the workers documentation.
[src:rq-queue/page] Sometimes you may want to suspend RQ to prevent it from processing new jobs.
[src:rq-queue/page] A classic example is during the initial phase of a deployment script or in advance of putting your site into maintenance mode.
[src:rq-queue/page] This is particularly helpful when you have jobs that are relatively long-running and might otherwise be forcibly killed during the deploy.
[src:rq-queue/page] The `suspend` command stops workers on *all* queues (in a single Redis database) from picking up new jobs.
[src:rq-queue/page] However currently running jobs will continue until completion.
[src:rq-queue/page] Technically, you can put any Python function call on a queue, but that does not mean it’s always wise to do so.
[src:rq-queue/page] RQ workers will only run on systems that implement `fork()`.
[src:rq-queue/page] Most notably, this means it is not possible to run the workers on Windows without using the Windows Subsystem for Linux and running in a bash shell.
[src:rq-queue/patterns] The details are from the ‘settings’ page of your Redis add-on on the Heroku dashboard.
[src:rq-queue/patterns] Foreman is probably the process manager you use when you host your app on Heroku, or just because it’s a pretty friendly tool to use in development.
[src:rq-queue/patterns] When using RQ under `foreman`, you may experience that the workers are a bit quiet sometimes.
[src:rq-queue/patterns] This is because of Python buffering the output, so `foreman` cannot (yet) echo it.
[src:rq-queue/python-rq-org] RQ (*Redis Queue*) is a simple Python library for queueing jobs and processing them in the background with workers.
[src:rq-queue/python-rq-org] It is backed by Redis/Valkey and is designed to have a low barrier to entry.
[src:rq-queue/python-rq-org] It integrates easily with your web or application stack.
[src:rq-queue/python-rq-org] RQ requires Redis >= 5 or Valkey >= 7.2.
[src:rq-queue/python-rq-org] Note that jobs will only repeat after successful executions.
[src:rq-queue/python-rq-org] `Job`: contains the function to be executed by the worker.
[src:rq-queue/python-rq-org] `Worker`: responsible for getting `Job` instances from a `Queue` and executing them.
[src:rq-queue/python-rq-org] `Execution`: contains runtime data of a `Job`, created by a `Worker` when it executes a `Job`.
[src:rq-queue/python-rq-org] `Result`: stores the outcome of an `Execution`, whether it succeeded or failed.
[src:rq-queue/python-rq-org] This project has been inspired by the good parts of Celery, Resque and this snippet, and has been created as a lightweight alternative to existing queueing frameworks, with a low barrier to entry.
[src:rq-queue/redis] The project was developed and maintained by Salvatore Sanfilippo, starting in 2009.
[src:rq-queue/redis] From 2015 until 2020, he led a project core team sponsored by Redis Labs.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Salvatore Sanfilippo left Redis as the maintainer in 2020.
[src:rq-queue/redis] In 2021 Redis Labs dropped the Labs from its name and now is known simply as "Redis".
[src:rq-queue/redis] In 2018, some modules for Redis adopted a modified Apache 2.0 license with a Commons Clause.
[src:rq-queue/redis] In 2024, the main Redis code switched from the open-source BSD-3 license to being dual-licensed under the Redis Source Available License v2 and the Server Side Public License v1.
[src:rq-queue/redis] On May 1, 2025, Redis became tri-licensed beginning with version 8.0, with the GNU Affero General Public License as the third option.
[src:rq-queue/redis] The name *Redis* means Remote Dictionary Server.
[src:rq-queue/redis] The Redis project began when Salvatore Sanfilippo (nicknamed *antirez*) was trying to improve the scalability of his Italian startup and developed a real-time web log analyzer.
[src:rq-queue/redis] After encountering significant problems in scaling some types of workloads using traditional database systems, Sanfilippo began in 2009 to prototype a first proof of concept version of Redis in Tcl.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Later, Sanfilippo translated that prototype to the C language and implemented the first data type, the list.
[src:rq-queue/redis] After a few weeks of using the project internally with success, Sanfilippo decided to open source it, announcing the project on Hacker News.
[src:rq-queue/redis] The project began to get traction, particularly among the Ruby community, with GitHub and Instagram being among the first companies adopting it.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Sanfilippo was hired by VMware in March 2010.
[src:rq-queue/redis] In May 2013, Redis was sponsored by Pivotal Software (a VMware spin-off).
[src:rq-queue/redis] In June 2015, development became sponsored by Redis Ltd.
[src:rq-queue/redis] This made the modules source-available and no longer free software.
[src:rq-queue/redis] The core Redis software remained under a BSD license, with Redis Ltd. committing to maintaining these terms.
[src:rq-queue/redis] In October 2018, Redis 5.0 was released, introducing Redis Stream – a new data structure that allows storage of multiple fields and string values with an automatic, time-based sequence at a single key.
[src:rq-queue/redis] In June 2020, Salvatore Sanfilippo stepped down as Redis' sole maintainer.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Sanfilippo was succeeded by Yossi Gottlieb and Oran Agra.
[src:rq-queue/redis] In March 2024, Redis Ltd. announced that beginning with version 7.4, the core Redis software would be relicensed under the RSAL and Server Side Public License (SSPL), both of which are source-available and non-free.
[src:rq-queue/redis] The Linux Foundation subsequently announced that it would fork the last BSD-licensed version of Redis as Valkey.
[src:rq-queue/redis] In May 2025, Redis Ltd. announced that it would change the license again to the AGPL beginning on version 8.0, citing that forks had achieved their goal of creating a "level playing field" of differentiated products, and that Redis has achieved "record growth" since the change in license.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Sanfilippo returned to Redis in December 2024.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Redis is a system that functions as both a data store and a cache.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Data is modified and read from the main computer memory while also being persisted to disk in a format optimized for sequential access rather than random access.
[src:rq-queue/redis] The formatted data is only reconstructed into memory once the system restarts.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Redis uses a data model that differs from relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:rq-queue/redis] Commands specify operations on abstract data types rather than queries to be executed by a database engine.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Data is stored in structures designed for direct retrieval.
[src:rq-queue/redis] It does not rely on secondary indexes, aggregations, or other features common in traditional RDBMS.
[src:rq-queue/redis] The Redis implementation uses the fork system call to duplicate the process holding the data.
[src:rq-queue/redis] This allows the parent process to continue serving clients while the child process persists the in-memory data to disk.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Redis supports a number of data types including Strings, JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) documents, Hashes (a collection of fields, each field is a name-value string pair), lists, sets, vector sets, and more.
[src:rq-queue/redis] The Redis Query Engine allows users to use Redis as a document database, a vector database, a secondary index, and a search engine.
[src:rq-queue/redis] With Redis Query Engine, users can define indexes for hash and JSON documents, and use a rich query language for vector search, full-text search, geospatial queries, and aggregations.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Redis Pub/Sub (short for publish/subscribe) is a lightweight messaging capability.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Publishers send messages to a channel, and subscribers receive messages from that channel.
[src:rq-queue/redis] A Redis transaction allows the execution of a group of commands in a single step.
[src:rq-queue/redis] A request sent by another client will never be served during the execution of a transaction.
[src:rq-queue/redis] This guarantees that the commands are executed as a single isolated operation.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Redis users can also upload and execute Lua scripts on the server.
[src:rq-queue/redis] As of May 1, 2025, for all version of Redis starting with 8.0, all data types are included in the same package and available under the Redis Source Available license v2.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Previously some data types were separate and therefore available under difference licenses.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Redis typically holds the whole dataset in memory.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Versions up to 2.4 could be configured to use what they refer to as virtual memory in which some of the dataset is stored on disk, but this feature is deprecated.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Redis can rewrite the append-only file in the background to avoid an indefinite growth of the journal.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Journaling was introduced in version 1.1 and is generally considered the safer approach.
[src:rq-queue/redis] By default, Redis writes data to a file system at least every two seconds, with more or less robust options available if needed.
[src:rq-queue/redis] In the case of a complete system failure on default settings, only a few seconds of data will be lost.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Redis supports master–replica replication.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Data from any Redis server can replicate to any number of replicas.
[src:rq-queue/redis] A replica may be a master to another replica.
[src:rq-queue/redis] This allows Redis to implement a single-rooted replication tree.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Redis replicas can be configured to accept writes, permitting intentional and unintentional inconsistency between instances.
[src:rq-queue/redis] The publish–subscribe feature is fully implemented, so a client of a replica may subscribe to a channel and receive a full feed of messages published to the master, anywhere up the replication tree.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Replication is useful for read (but not write) scalability or data redundancy.
[src:rq-queue/redis] When the durability of data is not needed, the in-memory nature of Redis allows it to perform well compared to database systems that write every change to disk before considering a transaction committed.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Redis operates as a single process and is single-threaded or double-threaded when it rewrites the AOF (append-only file).
[src:rq-queue/redis] Thus, a single Redis instance cannot use parallel execution of tasks such as stored procedures.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Redis introduced clustering in April 2015 with the release of version 3.0.
[src:rq-queue/redis] The cluster specification implements a subset of Redis commands: all single-key commands are available, multi-key operations (commands related to unions and intersections) are restricted to keys belonging to the same node, and commands related to database selection operations are unavailable.
[src:rq-queue/redis] A Redis cluster can scale up to 1,000 nodes, achieve "acceptable" write safety and to continue operations when some nodes fail.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Redis has been used by Adobe, Airbnb, Amazon, Hulu, OpenAI, Salesforce, Shopify, Tinder, Twitter, and Yahoo.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Typical use cases of Redis are session caching, full page cache, message queue applications, leaderboards and counting among others.
[src:rq-queue/redis] The publish–subscribe messaging paradigm allows real-time communication between servers.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Amazon Web Services offers a managed Redis service called ElastiCache for Redis, Google offers a managed Redis service called Cloud Memorystore, Microsoft offers Azure Cache for Redis in Azure, and Alibaba offers ApsaraDB for Redis in Alibaba Cloud.
[src:rq-queue/redis] Redis is interfaced with by various libraries.
[src:rq-queue/redis] For example, POCO C++ Libraries supports interfacing with Redis through its `Poco::Redis` library.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:rq-queue/task-queue] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
